<br>
1. Class Balance: more efficient nukes, group friendly buffs, various changes to existing useless spell lines (of wich we have our fair share=/), etc.<br>
<br>
2. Content Balance: melee resistant mobs that are highly vunerable to magic (bear in mind this gives all damage casters a boost not just wizards), swarms of mobs with low hp that are either unmezzable, or have extremely high dps, or are just too numerous to deal with without AE (this mostly calls for a wizards expertise), and others i probably haven't thought of<br>
<br>
<br>
Since it seems that discussing class balance only leads to endless threads full of bickering and boring damage logs:P perhpas we should spend some more time fosusing on the second school of thought.  <br>
<br>
For example, to those of you who subscribe to the philosophy of &quot;give me more efficient nukes or give me deah, snare and root be damned&quot; I say to you, lets add mobs that are less resistant to magic, but are immune to changes in thier run speed, and have rediculously high AC. <br>
<br>
That is just one example that I use to illustrate how content balance can be used to treat a class balance issue. Pehaps others can come up with some better content balance ideas.<br>
Lets put on our thinking caps.  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=176149">Pidd of the Nexus</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.aol.com/dbzgnome/images/piddsig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.geocities.com/adkinsband/OPA.txt" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.fortunecity.com/butterflysedge/ff8anigifs/mini_vivi.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=siryakk>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 163<br> <font color=#ffffff>(11/19/02 6:28 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: There are two schools of thought.....</span><hr size=1> A snarable, high AC, high DPS, low hp mob is ideal for a wizard.<br>
<br>
You fill a zone with them, and yes wizards become ungodly powerful.<br>
<br>
So much so, that you have no dependance on any support class.  A wizard becomes 100% capable of dealing with these mobs all alone.<br>
<br>
And if a wizard doesn't need support, support becomes inefficient.  You may as well not bring along warriors enchanters clerics shamans shadowknights rangers rogues monks paladins mages.  Druids and Necros kite the mobs as well, without any support, and bards can have fun charm kiting them.<br>
<br>
The problem with these mobs is that 4 classes require no aid to kill them.  No interdependance, other than a KEI ever 2.5 hours.<br>
